by Yooper High Kingdom » Mon Feb 14, 2022 11:15 am

South Reinkalistan wrote:
Yooper High Kingdom wrote:Well yeah, I was just saying that.

Also, with that whole time dilation thing, wouldn't that make any form of state outside of planetary regimes impossible if it could still take centuries for an army or communication to get from point-a to point-b? I mean, if I knew that Earth was gonna send an army to defeat my rebellion - several centuries is a rather generous timeframe to give me to prepare. By that point, they'd be several centuries behind technologically to a point where their weapons would be to us how muskets and cannons are to MT people.

That's actually an observed potential phenomenon tbh, but a good response to the whole time dilation debacle is fairly simple -- aren't there theoretical drives that don't actually "move" the ship but simply compact the immediate space in front of it and expand the immediate space behind it?

Alcubierre drives, yeah. The idea being that the drive doesn't actually move the ship per se, but rather squishes spacetime forward of it and stretches the spacetime behind it. So it doesn't move faster than light, it just makes the ride a lot physically shorter.

It's big brain physics stuff I don't understand, but its the least paradoxical "FTL" drive that doesn't straight up use physics breaking magic (in a soft FT sense, such as star wars drives) - so it's what I use for my projects where FTL is commonly used.

South Reinkalistan wrote:That's actually an observed potential phenomenon tbh, but a good response to the whole time dilation debacle is fairly simple -- aren't there theoretical drives that don't actually "move" the ship but simply compact the immediate space in front of it and expand the immediate space behind it?


The problem with Alcubierre drives is that it takes time to compress the space in front of the vessel. IIRC (and I CBA'd to go re-verify it so preemptive kudos to the incoming akschually post) the theoretical fastest would be 1LY/year.

EDIT: no it got the best of me and I looked it up:

For example, if one wanted to travel to Deneb (2,600 light-years away) and arrive less than 2,600 years in the future according to external clocks, it would be required that someone had already begun work on warping the space from Earth to Deneb at least 2,600 years ago:

A spaceship appropriately located with respect to the bubble trajectory could then choose to enter the bubble, rather like a passenger catching a passing trolley car, and thus make the superluminal journey ... as Krasnikov points out, causality considerations do not prevent the crew of a spaceship from arranging, by their own actions, to complete a round trip from Earth to a distant star and back in an arbitrarily short time, as measured by clocks on Earth, by altering the metric along the path of their outbound trip.
